=========================================================
RAII (Resource Acquisition Is Initialization)
=========================================================

Definition:
RAII is a C++ programming idiom in which resource acquisition happens in
the constructor and resource release happens in the destructor.

Interview Line:
"Bind resource lifetime to object lifetime."

=========================================================
WHY DO WE NEED RAII?
=========================================================

Without RAII:
• Memory leaks
• Resource leaks
• Exception safety issues
• Manual cleanup becomes difficult

With RAII:
• Automatic cleanup
• Exception safety
• No resource leaks
• Easier resource management

=========================================================
BASIC IDEA
=========================================================

Constructor
      ↓
Acquire Resource
      ↓
Use Resource
      ↓
Destructor
      ↓
Release Resource

=========================================================
CLASSIC EXAMPLE (WITHOUT RAII)
=========================================================

void fun()
{
    int* ptr = new int(10);

    // Exception occurs here

    delete ptr;
}

Problem:
If an exception occurs before delete,
memory leaks.

=========================================================
RAII SOLUTION
=========================================================

class Resource
{
    int* ptr;

public:
    Resource()
    {
        ptr = new int(10);
    }

    ~Resource()
    {
        delete ptr;
    }
};

void fun()
{
    Resource r;
}

Even if an exception occurs,
destructor runs automatically.

No memory leak.

=========================================================
EXCEPTION SAFETY
=========================================================

void fun()
{
    Resource r;

    throw runtime_error("Error");
}

Output:

Destructor still executes.

Resource released.

This is the biggest advantage of RAII.

=========================================================
REAL-WORLD EXAMPLES OF RAII
=========================================================

1. Smart Pointers
2. File Handling
3. Mutex Locking
4. Database Connections
5. Socket Management

=========================================================
SMART POINTER EXAMPLE
=========================================================

{
    unique_ptr<int> ptr =
        make_unique<int>(10);
}

Scope ends
↓
Destructor called
↓
Memory automatically released

=========================================================
FILE HANDLING EXAMPLE
=========================================================

{
    ifstream file("abc.txt");

    // Use file
}

Scope ends
↓
File automatically closed.

=========================================================
MUTEX EXAMPLE (VERY IMPORTANT)
=========================================================

std::mutex m;

void fun()
{
    std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(m);

    // Critical section
}

Scope ends
↓
lock_guard destructor executes
↓
Mutex automatically unlocked

Prevents deadlocks.

=========================================================
RAII IN STL
=========================================================

Examples:

vector<int>
string
fstream
thread wrappers
lock_guard
unique_ptr
shared_ptr

All follow RAII.

=========================================================
WHY IS RAII IMPORTANT IN C++?
=========================================================

C++ has deterministic destruction.

Objects are destroyed automatically when they go out of scope.

Therefore:

Destructor = Automatic cleanup.

RAII heavily relies on this feature.

=========================================================
RAII vs MANUAL RESOURCE MANAGEMENT
=========================================================

Feature                 Manual             RAII
------------------------------------------------------------
Cleanup                 Explicit           Automatic
Exception Safety        Poor               Excellent
Memory Leaks            Possible           Rare
Code Complexity         High               Low
Reliability             Lower              Higher

